==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Slough
<hw>Slough</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>slogh</ets>,
<ets>slough</ets>, AS. <ets>sl⟦omac⟧h</ets> a hollow place; cf. MHG.
<ets>sl⟦umac⟧ch</ets> an abyss, gullet, G. <ets>schlucken</ets> to
swallow; also Gael. & Ir. <ets>sloc</ets> a pit, pool. ditch, Ir.
<ets>slug</ets> to swallow. Gr. <?/<?/<?/<?/<?/ to hiccough, to
sob.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A place of deep mud or mire; a hole full of
mire.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He's here stuck in a <qex>slough</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <pr>[<it>Pronounced</it> sl⟦oomac⟧.]</pr> <def>A wet
place; a swale; a side channel or inlet from a river.</def> <note>[In
this sense local or provincial; also spelt <asp>sloo</asp>, and
<asp>slue</asp>.]</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Slough grass</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a name in
the Mississippi valley for grasses of the genus <gen>Muhlenbergia</gen>;
-- called also <altname>drop seed</altname>, and <altname>nimble
Will</altname>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slough</ent>⟦br⟧

