<p><ent>Slough</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Slough
<hw>Slough</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>slugh</ets>,
<ets>slouh</ets>; cf. MHG. <ets>sl<?/ch</ets> the skin of a serpent, G.
<ets>schlauch</ets> a skin, a leather bag or bottle.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The skin, commonly the cast-off skin, of a serpent or of some
similar animal.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>The dead mass separating from a
foul sore; the dead part which separates from the living tissue in
mortification.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slough</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Slough
<hw>Slough</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Sloughed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sloughing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>To form a
slough; to separate in the form of dead matter from the living tissues;
-- often used with <xex>off</xex>, or <xex>away</xex>; <as>as, a
<ex>sloughing</ex> ulcer; the dead tissues <ex>slough</ex> off
slowly.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slough</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Slough
<hw>Slough</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To cast off; to discard as
refuse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>New tint the plumage of the birds,⟦br⟧
And <qex>slough</qex> decay from grazing herds.</q>
<rj><qau>Emerson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sloughing</ent>⟦br⟧
